File: lichen/subsys/lichen/routing/loadng.c
Lines: 376-384

In prune_seen_locked():

    for (size_t i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(seen_table); i++) {
        if (seen_table[i].active &&
            (now_ms - seen_table[i].seen_at_ms) >= LICHEN_LOADNG_SUPPRESS_WINDOW_MS) {
            seen_table[i].active = false;
        }
    }

And in the duplicate check (lines 405-408):
    uint32_t elapsed = now_ms - seen_table[i].seen_at_ms;
    if (elapsed < LICHEN_LOADNG_SUPPRESS_WINDOW_MS) {

These calculations '(now_ms - seen_at_ms)' rely on unsigned wraparound, which works correctly for durations up to ~49 days. However, if an entry's seen_at_ms is in the future relative to now_ms (shouldn't happen but could due to time adjustment or bug), the subtraction produces a large positive value, causing:
1. Entry appears ancient and gets pruned
2. Or entry appears way beyond suppress window

While this edge case is unlikely, other similar timestamp code uses signed comparison for robustness. Consider: '(int32_t)(now_ms - seen_at_ms) >= (int32_t)LICHEN_LOADNG_SUPPRESS_WINDOW_MS'
